        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4074290409" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16471542981703486058"><strong>Casanova the later years</strong><br/><br/>I love it when someone takes it upon themselves to give a narrative to historical events and people and in this book The Devils Doorbell, I think the author did a fantastic job. Originally historians thought Casanova’s life ended at least the fancy one he knew in his older years, but after digging in old basements and FiOS people thought lost we find out he didn’t. Not only did he live well in his older years but in this book he takes it upon his self to teach young jock,</span>
  <span id="freeText16471542981703486058" style="display:none"><strong>Casanova the later years</strong><br /><br />I love it when someone takes it upon themselves to give a narrative to historical events and people and in this book The Devils Doorbell, I think the author did a fantastic job. Originally historians thought Casanova’s life ended at least the fancy one he knew in his older years, but after digging in old basements and FiOS people thought lost we find out he didn’t. Not only did he live well in his older years but in this book he takes it upon his self to teach young jock, Everything he knew and everything there is to know about love, women, life etc. at first Jack is reluctant, but then gets caught up in Casanova‘s charm and the adventure begins. This is a very interesting and intriguing account of Casanova’s is an elderly gentleman who still spry and ready for love. I totally enjoyed it found it thoroughly entertaining and highly recommend it!</span>
